>
  <p data-reveal>One of the questions I hear most — sometimes spoken, sometimes implied — is this: is what I'm going through enough to justify therapy? As if you had to earn the right to ask for help with a certain amount of suffering. As if therapy were an emergency resource, rather than what it actually is: a space for self-knowledge, growth, and honest self-review.</p>
  <p data-reveal>There's no minimum threshold of pain required to begin. There are, however, moments when life invites us — sometimes gently, sometimes forcefully — to stop and look at ourselves.</p>

  <h2 data-reveal>Therapy isn't only for crises</h2>
  <p data-reveal>Some people come to my practice at the worst moment of their lives. Others arrive when things are going well, but they sense something could be better — that certain patterns keep repeating, that relationships have a ceiling they don't understand, that there's a distance between the life they have and the one they sense is possible.</p>
  <p data-reveal>Both are valid reasons. And in both cases, the process can be profound.</p>
  <p data-reveal>I think of therapy the way I think of exercise or meditation: nobody waits to get sick before moving. Sustained psychological work — week after week, with continuity — builds a capacity for emotional regulation, self-observation, and self-relationship that changes how everything else is lived. It's not a luxury or a sign of weakness. It's a practice.</p>
  <p data-reveal>In my approach, rooted in <a href="/en/blog/core-energetics/" class="link-underline">Core Energetics</a> and in the somatic work I learned from my teacher Lael Keen, self-knowledge isn't only conceptual: it means knowing how your body responds, what patterns are encoded in your nervous system, what family stories keep operating in you without your having chosen them. That work doesn't require crisis. It requires curiosity and willingness.</p>
  <p data-reveal>If you're wondering how that process works from the start, you can read <a href="/en/blog/first-session/" class="link-underline">What's a first session usually like?</a> or <a href="/en/blog/what-to-expect/" class="link-underline">What to expect from therapy?</a></p>

  <h2 data-reveal>When the body speaks before the mind does</h2>
  <p data-reveal>Sometimes the moment to begin doesn't arrive as a rational decision. It arrives as a symptom.</p>
  <p data-reveal>Gabor Maté has rigorously documented how sustained stress and emotional repression express themselves in the body: autoimmune disease, chronic pain, unexplained fatigue, digestive issues. The body doesn't lie — it simply speaks in a language we don't always know how to read. When there's tension that won't ease, insomnia with no apparent cause, a constant sense of alertness or emptiness, the body is saying something worth listening to.</p>
  <p data-reveal>The same happens emotionally: surprising irritability, sadness that won't pass, anxiety with no clear name, difficulty staying present in relationships. Or relationally: conflicts that repeat with different people but the same script, distance that grows without understanding why, an inability to truly connect with the people who matter most.</p>
  <p data-reveal>None of these signs require you to be "at the limit" before taking them seriously. Quite the opposite: the sooner they're addressed, the more flexibility there is to work with them. <a href="/en/blog/body-based-therapy/" class="link-underline">Body-based therapy</a> and <a href="/en/blog/somatic-experiencing/" class="link-underline">Somatic Experiencing</a> offer specific tools to work with what the body registers before the mind can articulate it.</p>

  <h2 data-reveal>The myths that delay the decision</h2>
  <p data-reveal>There are some ideas that act as brakes. I hear them often, and they're worth looking at directly.</p>
  <p data-reveal>"I'll figure this out on my own first." Sometimes, yes, you can. But most patterns that generate distress aren't resolved by willpower alone — they're resolved in relationship, with someone else. Therapy isn't giving up; it's recognizing that certain things are seen more clearly with support. It's an act of intelligence, not weakness.</p>
  <p data-reveal>"Therapy is for people with serious problems." This is perhaps the most widespread myth. Therapy is for anyone who wants to know themselves better, live with more awareness, relate more authentically. There's no severity threshold. There's a decision to attend to what's asking for attention.</p>
  <p data-reveal>"I don't have the time or money right now." This one is real and deserves respect — not everyone has access, and that's a structural problem that exists. But when this argument keeps coming up, it's also worth asking: where does this sit on my list of priorities? The time and money we don't invest in ourselves tend to get spent later remedying what could have been addressed earlier.</p>

  <h2 data-reveal>Life's invitation</h2>
  <p data-reveal>There are moments when something breaks — a relationship, a project, an image of yourself — and that break opens a crack through which light gets in. A loss, a rupture, a crisis of meaning. It's not a coincidence. Life, in its own way, pushes us toward where we need to go.</p>
  <p data-reveal>In my clinical experience, the most transformative processes don't always begin at the worst moment. Sometimes they begin when someone simply decides they want to live with more presence, more inner freedom, more honest relationships. That, too, is an invitation. And it also deserves to be taken seriously.</p>
  <p data-reveal>If something you read here resonates, it might be a good time to take the first step. You can start with <a href="/en/blog/first-session/" class="link-underline">What's a first session usually like?</a> to know what to expect from the initial process.</p>
